WEBVTT

00:01.627 --> 00:04.050
MORRIS: Mrs. Owen is expecting
a lot of guests.

00:04.171 --> 00:05.764
She chose you.

00:05.881 --> 00:07.349
Welcome to Soldier Island.

00:07.925 --> 00:10.223
VERA: Mr. Lombard, you seem
to be under the impression

00:10.344 --> 00:12.438
that I am a particular kind
of woman.

00:12.554 --> 00:14.477
And I assure you that I'm not.

00:14.598 --> 00:16.190
VERA: They're the 10
little soldiers --

00:16.308 --> 00:17.776
you know, from the poem.

00:17.893 --> 00:19.315
MAN ON LOUDSPEAKER:
Ladies and gentlemen...

00:19.436 --> 00:20.312
Who is that?

00:20.437 --> 00:21.654
MAN ON LOUDSPEAKER:
You are charged

00:21.772 --> 00:23.319
with the following indictments.

00:23.440 --> 00:26.569
Philip Lombard --
that you did murder 21 men.

00:26.693 --> 00:29.071
What the hell
are they playing at?!

00:29.196 --> 00:30.664
Malicious nonsense.

00:30.781 --> 00:33.455
Cyril.
I really tried to save him.

00:33.575 --> 00:35.122
I almost drowned.

00:35.244 --> 00:36.211
Twenty-one men?

00:36.328 --> 00:39.923
I'm the only one telling the
truth in a room full of liars.

00:40.040 --> 00:41.462
-[ Knock on door]
- Who is it?

00:42.668 --> 00:44.796
MacARTHUR:
We are cut off.

00:45.379 --> 00:47.006
Rats in a barrel.

00:47.130 --> 00:48.552
Almonds.

00:48.674 --> 00:50.893
Almonds be buggered.

00:51.009 --> 00:52.181
Cyanide.

00:52.302 --> 00:55.476
[ Dramatic music plays]

00:57.000 --> 01:03.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

02:06.460 --> 02:08.508
None of you moved them?

02:09.086 --> 02:11.055
- No.
- No.

02:11.173 --> 02:12.891
Was it you, Doctor?

02:14.551 --> 02:15.928
No.

02:18.722 --> 02:21.100
How did Mrs. Rogers die?

02:22.517 --> 02:23.609
I have no idea.

02:23.727 --> 02:25.525
Did you give her something?

02:25.646 --> 02:27.523
Yes -- a mild sedative.

02:27.648 --> 02:29.025
VERA:
Did you give her too much?

02:29.149 --> 02:32.904
Miss Claythorne, I warned you
against becoming hysterical.

02:33.028 --> 02:34.405
It's the poem.

02:34.529 --> 02:36.748
It's the poem.
Don't you see?

02:36.865 --> 02:38.583
Ten little soldier boys.

02:38.700 --> 02:41.294
One choked himself,
one overslept himself,

02:41.411 --> 02:42.333
and then there were eight.

02:42.454 --> 02:44.172
There were 10 of these
and 10 of us,

02:44.289 --> 02:45.757
and now there's eight.

02:45.874 --> 02:47.126
[ Door opens]

02:47.709 --> 02:50.508
Oh, General -- General,
did you move the figures?

02:50.629 --> 02:51.676
What?

02:51.797 --> 02:53.595
The figures.
Did you move the figures?

02:53.715 --> 02:55.308
No.
Of course not.

02:55.425 --> 02:57.018
DR. ARMSTRONG: Perhaps
it was you, Miss Claythorne.

02:57.135 --> 02:59.229
- You discovered it.
- Of course it wasn't me.

02:59.346 --> 03:01.599
- Why would I do that?
- To be the center of attention.

03:01.723 --> 03:03.270
Do you crave attention,
Miss Claythorne?

03:03.392 --> 03:05.110
Any kind of attention?

03:05.227 --> 03:07.855
- What are you talking about?
- Shall we just have breakfast?

03:08.522 --> 03:09.694
Mm-hmm.

03:12.484 --> 03:16.739
It was dreadful news
about Mrs. Rogers.

03:16.863 --> 03:18.831
She was a wonderful cook.

03:18.949 --> 03:20.747
Such a shame.

03:21.451 --> 03:25.331
Uh, this egg is four minutes
precisely, is it?

03:27.916 --> 03:29.634
Yes, madam.

03:29.751 --> 03:33.506
Rogers, did you take away
two of these figures?

03:33.630 --> 03:34.677
<i>No, miss.</i>

03:34.798 --> 03:37.017
-[ Sighs ]
- Condolences, Mr. Rogers.

03:37.134 --> 03:39.136
When are you expecting
Narracott?

03:39.261 --> 03:40.558
Mid- to late morning, sir.

03:40.679 --> 03:42.807
His timekeeping
is somewhat erratic.

03:44.349 --> 03:45.976
Will that be all?

03:46.101 --> 03:48.695
Yes. Thank you, Rogers.
Thank you very much.

03:50.647 --> 03:53.491
VERA: Tony Marston was young
and strong.

03:53.608 --> 03:56.578
He didn't die
from some stimulant.

03:56.695 --> 03:58.038
Perhaps he was poisoned.

03:58.155 --> 04:01.580
And -- And Mrs. Rogers --
perhaps she was given too much.

04:01.700 --> 04:04.499
What drugs do you have
in your medical bag, Doctor?

04:04.619 --> 04:06.997
Why did you even bring it?

04:07.122 --> 04:08.795
You are a guest.
It's not work.

04:08.915 --> 04:10.917
Actually, it <i>is</i> work.

04:11.042 --> 04:15.138
I was trying to maintain some
sort of professional discretion.

04:15.255 --> 04:20.226
However, Mrs. Owen suffers from
female neuroses.

04:20.343 --> 04:23.142
My speciality
is women's disorders.

04:24.014 --> 04:26.767
Mr. Owen engaged me
in a professional capacity

04:26.892 --> 04:28.394
to tend to his wife!

04:28.518 --> 04:30.065
Gave up on the surgery, then,
Doctor?

04:30.187 --> 04:33.407
VERA: No. People do not just die
out of nowhere for no reason.

04:33.523 --> 04:37.244
They die because something
was done to them by someone.

04:37.360 --> 04:38.532
I'm gonna check your bag.

04:38.653 --> 04:40.701
- Don't you dare touch --
- What have you got to hide?

04:40.822 --> 04:42.074
How about I do it?

04:43.617 --> 04:46.120
I'm not being searched
like some grubby criminal.

04:46.244 --> 04:49.043
Then what if the general
goes with him?

04:49.164 --> 04:50.791
He's an honorable man.

04:50.916 --> 04:51.963
DR. ARMSTRONG:
Fine!

04:52.083 --> 04:52.959
But while you're at it,

04:53.084 --> 04:56.930
you might want to search
Judge Wargrave's case as well.

04:57.047 --> 04:58.845
I know where I've seen you
before.

04:59.549 --> 05:02.223
Chap who has the clinic
beneath mine in Harley Street,

05:02.344 --> 05:03.436
he's a cancer specialist.

05:03.553 --> 05:05.180
That's where I saw you.

05:05.305 --> 05:08.434
If anyone has strong painkillers
and sedatives in his case,

05:08.558 --> 05:09.810
it's Judge Wargrave.

05:11.895 --> 05:13.863
Is that true, Judge?

05:14.439 --> 05:17.693
I have had health problems, yes.

05:17.818 --> 05:19.445
Then that's very cruel, Doctor.

05:19.569 --> 05:21.663
Don't blame me.
You pushed it.

05:21.780 --> 05:24.329
General, shall we?

05:28.161 --> 05:31.085
[Clock ticking ]

05:33.250 --> 05:36.049
Just mild sedatives.

05:36.169 --> 05:37.921
DR. ARMSTRONG:
As I said.

05:38.046 --> 05:39.844
Bog-standard.

05:39.965 --> 05:41.262
Nothing special.

05:41.383 --> 05:44.603
My surgery was a success.

05:44.719 --> 05:50.647
This -- the house, the island --
is meant to be my recuperation.

05:50.767 --> 05:56.115
Sea air, peace...and rest.

05:56.982 --> 05:59.826
Very sorry.
I'm...very sorry.

05:59.943 --> 06:01.195
Mm.

06:02.195 --> 06:03.447
Well, there's an end to it.

06:03.572 --> 06:05.324
Like hell it is.

06:05.448 --> 06:07.041
Why shouldn't she be searched?

06:08.785 --> 06:10.833
Equal rights for women.

06:10.954 --> 06:13.548
Hmm?
Let's see what you've got.

06:13.665 --> 06:17.966
WARGRAVE: Dr. Armstrong,
control yourself, please.

06:23.300 --> 06:25.473
Who the hell
do you think you are?

06:26.428 --> 06:28.681
I'm a doctor.
You're a secretary.

06:35.770 --> 06:37.443
VERA:
Somebody moved them.

06:39.024 --> 06:40.617
They did.

06:40.734 --> 06:42.736
Someone did that.

06:48.408 --> 06:50.581
[ Birds crying in distance]

06:50.702 --> 06:52.579
[ Door opens]

06:52.704 --> 06:54.957
[ Footsteps approaching ]

07:09.596 --> 07:11.940
Did you really kill
all those men?

07:14.643 --> 07:18.568
Yes, Miss Claythorne.
I did kill all those men.

07:19.272 --> 07:20.945
And more.

07:21.608 --> 07:23.235
Why?

07:23.360 --> 07:26.364
It seemed like a good idea
at the time.

07:27.656 --> 07:29.124
They had something I wanted.

07:29.240 --> 07:31.743
In this case, it was diamonds.

07:32.619 --> 07:34.872
Worth more than a few lives.

07:35.789 --> 07:37.791
What about you?

07:41.920 --> 07:43.763
What did you want?

07:45.674 --> 07:47.972
I nearly drowned.

07:48.802 --> 07:51.806
I failed to save a little boy
in my care.

07:51.930 --> 07:53.648
And there isn't one minute
of every day

07:53.765 --> 07:55.859
that I am not sorry for that.

07:57.143 --> 07:58.770
Why aren't you?

07:58.895 --> 08:00.897
I know what I am.

08:01.982 --> 08:04.986
I always knew
it would catch up with me.

08:06.528 --> 08:08.530
And here it is.

09:01.166 --> 09:04.090
[ Explosions in distance]

09:12.010 --> 09:14.638
WOMAN: I love you,
I love you, I love you.

09:14.763 --> 09:16.936
I think about you
and you kissing me

09:17.057 --> 09:19.651
and your hands on me and in me
and your mouth on my body,

09:19.768 --> 09:23.272
and I cannot bear
that you are not with me now.

09:23.396 --> 09:27.697
I wish, I long,
I crave for you, my darling,

09:27.817 --> 09:32.243
and I feel so cruel
to poor, dear John,

09:32.363 --> 09:35.207
but the sun rises and sets
in your eyes, Henry.

09:35.992 --> 09:39.792
I love you.
I love you.

09:39.913 --> 09:41.711
I am yours.“

09:42.207 --> 09:45.006
The men are all ready
for the whistle, sir.

09:45.126 --> 09:47.424
Morale fairly good.

09:51.800 --> 09:54.724
[ Explosions in distance]

09:57.097 --> 09:59.475
Here.
Uh, let me.

10:05.313 --> 10:06.656
Henry.

10:10.860 --> 10:17.539
You've been <i>a...</i>
a great friend to my wife and I.

10:23.665 --> 10:26.009
Perhaps you could call me John.

10:31.422 --> 10:34.016
Thank you, John.

10:37.846 --> 10:39.723
[Gunshot]

10:39.848 --> 10:42.146
[ Inhales sharply]

10:42.267 --> 10:44.770
[ Breathing heavily]

10:50.400 --> 10:52.619
Myself and Mrs. Rogers were here
for a week

10:52.735 --> 10:54.112
without seeing another soul

10:54.237 --> 10:56.990
apart from Narracott
with the delivery, sir.

11:01.995 --> 11:02.996
Lombard.

11:04.455 --> 11:05.832
Where are you going?

11:05.957 --> 11:09.552
We're sat around
waiting for Ulick Norman Owen.

11:09.669 --> 11:11.763
What if he's been here
all along?

11:13.840 --> 11:16.343
Plenty of places
he could be hiding.

11:17.468 --> 11:18.845
Wait for me.

11:27.729 --> 11:30.027
[ Breathing shakily]

11:51.794 --> 11:56.140
Please, please,
please just fucking stop.

11:56.257 --> 12:00.228
Stop.
S-Stop. Stop. Stop.

12:16.611 --> 12:20.241
BLORE:
Oh, this is -- this is barmy!

12:21.824 --> 12:23.701
No one could hide down there.

12:23.826 --> 12:25.920
[ Bird crying ]

12:32.877 --> 12:36.256
Ever get the feeling
you're being hunted, Tubs?

12:36.381 --> 12:38.975
Now, stop calling me that.
I ain't even fat.

12:39.550 --> 12:41.348
And no, I don't.

12:41.469 --> 12:42.937
Really?

12:44.138 --> 12:49.395
'Cause Mr. Owen, whoever he may
be, knows a lot about us.

12:49.519 --> 12:51.738
Well, not about me.

12:51.854 --> 12:54.983
Edward Landor was a degenerate.
He was a pansy.

12:55.108 --> 12:58.157
He fell down the steps
into his cell.

13:07.704 --> 13:09.672
You never touched him?

13:11.207 --> 13:14.336
I wouldn't want to be near
one of them dirty bastards.

13:17.297 --> 13:19.299
Come on, Tubs!
Keep up!

13:21.134 --> 13:23.637
[Birds calling]

13:32.979 --> 13:34.572
General?

13:34.689 --> 13:36.783
Is your suitcase ready?

13:39.444 --> 13:41.287
She died.

13:42.280 --> 13:46.205
Spanish influenza,
after the war.

13:46.743 --> 13:47.790
Who?

13:49.412 --> 13:51.585
My wife, Leslie.

13:52.206 --> 13:57.178
After all that...
she died of the Spanish flu.

14:02.258 --> 14:04.226
So many did.

14:04.344 --> 14:08.599
I should have just stepped aside
like a gentleman and...

14:08.723 --> 14:11.101
just let them be happy.

14:13.811 --> 14:16.906
Do come back to the house,
General.

14:17.398 --> 14:18.991
You haven't
brought your case down yet,

14:19.108 --> 14:22.658
and we want to get away <i>as</i> soon
as Mr. Narracott arrives.

14:25.198 --> 14:27.917
He's not coming, Narracott,
you know.

14:28.034 --> 14:30.457
No one's coming for us.

14:30.953 --> 14:32.626
We won't be leaving the island.

14:32.747 --> 14:34.044
This is the end.

14:37.085 --> 14:41.090
It's a relief to come to
the end, to know that it's over.

14:41.672 --> 14:44.676
You won't understand that yet,
but you will --

14:44.801 --> 14:46.678
in time.

14:48.596 --> 14:50.724
I think you're quite mistaken.

14:51.974 --> 14:55.023
The boat will come and we'll all
be waiting for you.

15:06.197 --> 15:08.370
[ Gunfire, explosions
in distance]

15:29.554 --> 15:32.057
[ Gunfire, explosions continue]

15:52.034 --> 15:54.002
Ah, Miss Claythorne.

15:54.579 --> 15:55.580
Good.

15:56.205 --> 15:58.549
Bring a couple of chairs,
would you'?

16:03.588 --> 16:06.091
[ Clattering in distance]

16:07.967 --> 16:09.685
What's going on?

16:09.802 --> 16:11.975
It's a bit early
to be on the sauce.

16:12.847 --> 16:14.394
It's been something
of a morning.

16:14.515 --> 16:18.065
Hey. Hey.
Shh.

16:20.771 --> 16:23.900
Bastard's down there.
I heard him.

16:24.025 --> 16:25.151
What bastard?

16:26.360 --> 16:27.577
Owen.

16:27.695 --> 16:30.118
PHILIP:
I can hear him moving about.

16:30.698 --> 16:32.245
Marston's room.

16:32.366 --> 16:34.869
[ Clattering continues]

16:54.722 --> 16:58.022
[ Breathing heavily]

16:58.142 --> 16:59.985
What are you doing?

17:02.605 --> 17:03.857
[ Clattering ]

17:06.358 --> 17:07.906
Camp bed.

17:08.027 --> 17:11.076
Well, we had to find somewhere
to store it, and...

17:11.196 --> 17:13.244
young men don't look under beds.

17:13.366 --> 17:15.289
But w-what do you need
a camp bed for?

17:15.409 --> 17:16.535
What were you planning?

17:16.661 --> 17:18.959
Well, I can't sleep in my room,
can I?

17:19.079 --> 17:20.127
Me wife.

17:20.248 --> 17:22.592
Yeah. Obviously.
Of course.

17:23.251 --> 17:25.378
I've got to find somewhere else
to set up.

17:25.502 --> 17:27.130
What for?
We're all leaving.

17:27.255 --> 17:30.225
Well, you might be.
This is my job.

17:30.341 --> 17:32.890
I can't go anywhere
until my employer dismisses me.

17:33.010 --> 17:35.604
Your employer?
Your employer is insane.

17:35.721 --> 17:40.067
Be that as it may,
I've got nothing else to go to.

17:41.310 --> 17:43.654
All right, then.
Carry on, Rogers.

17:49.694 --> 17:52.322
Did you know he had a gun?

17:52.446 --> 17:53.948
No.

18:04.584 --> 18:07.087
[ Birds crying in distance]

18:08.337 --> 18:10.214
Do stop.

18:10.339 --> 18:12.592
Mr. Narracott seems
a sensible man.

18:12.717 --> 18:14.219
He'll be here.

18:17.471 --> 18:20.350
I must say, I understand now

18:20.474 --> 18:24.229
why you teach in such
a substandard establishment.

18:26.147 --> 18:28.821
I'm just observing
that most schools

18:28.941 --> 18:31.490
would not want to be associated
with an inquest.

18:31.611 --> 18:32.828
I'm not accusing you.

18:32.945 --> 18:34.947
There's been quite enough
of that already.

18:35.072 --> 18:36.449
Yes, there has.

18:36.574 --> 18:37.996
More than enough.

18:38.117 --> 18:40.336
Apart from the egregious
Mr. Lombard

18:40.453 --> 18:43.127
and the Rogers,
who I find most dubious,

18:43.247 --> 18:48.344
and the depraved Mr. Marston,
it's all nonsense.

18:48.461 --> 18:51.431
Everyone was simply doing
their duty.

18:52.006 --> 18:53.474
As was I.

18:54.800 --> 18:55.926
As were you?

18:56.052 --> 18:58.805
You didn't say anything
last night.

18:59.513 --> 19:01.766
It wasn't for gentlemen's ears.

19:01.891 --> 19:05.145
But Beatrice Taylor was my maid
of all work.

19:06.520 --> 19:08.397
Foundling girl.

19:08.522 --> 19:13.528
An unwanted --
from the war, you know?

19:14.570 --> 19:16.117
[ Birds chirping ]

19:16.238 --> 19:20.118
I believed her to be a clean,
decent, modest girl.

19:20.242 --> 19:22.495
I taught her needlework skills.

19:22.620 --> 19:24.668
We had quite the little home.

19:49.772 --> 19:52.116
But then she got herself
into trouble.

19:52.942 --> 19:54.615
The family way.

19:56.320 --> 20:00.917
As her own loose mother had
with her.

20:01.409 --> 20:03.753
She begged me for help.

20:04.328 --> 20:07.548
Naturally and quite properly,
I refused.

20:07.665 --> 20:10.839
[ Sobbing ]

20:13.838 --> 20:16.307
Miss Brent, please!

20:20.845 --> 20:22.643
I beg you!

20:24.849 --> 20:26.396
What happened to her?

20:26.517 --> 20:28.235
She threw herself under a train.

20:28.352 --> 20:29.979
She killed herself?

20:30.104 --> 20:32.198
Even made the local paper.

20:32.773 --> 20:36.903
And they turned it into some
potboiling sentimental tale.

20:37.528 --> 20:39.405
She asked you for help.

20:39.530 --> 20:40.531
If you had helped her --

20:40.656 --> 20:42.374
It was the weakness
in her character

20:42.491 --> 20:44.368
which drove her actions.

20:44.493 --> 20:46.040
Why should <i>I</i> be reproached?

20:46.162 --> 20:48.836
[Thunder rumbles]

20:50.791 --> 20:52.668
Ask Rogers for some tea.

20:56.380 --> 20:58.303
Lemon, not milk.

21:04.889 --> 21:07.108
DR. ARMSTRONG: It's a
wild-goose chase if you ask me.

21:07.224 --> 21:09.898
Grown man hiding
and sneaking about.

21:10.019 --> 21:10.941
It's ridiculous.

21:11.061 --> 21:14.190
Marston was given cyanide,
though.

21:14.690 --> 21:15.612
Wasn't he, Tubs?

21:15.733 --> 21:17.280
Cyanide?

21:17.777 --> 21:20.030
I'm pretty sure of it.

21:20.154 --> 21:22.122
[ Snorts ]
I don't know.

21:22.239 --> 21:24.913
You were convinced of it
this morning.

21:27.787 --> 21:29.960
Claythorne for the cyanide.

21:30.080 --> 21:32.253
- I’d put money on it.
- She don't seem the type.

21:32.374 --> 21:33.626
No.
She's exactly the type.

21:33.751 --> 21:37.005
What about the old boy,
the general?

21:37.129 --> 21:39.382
Dangerous men come back,
you know, from over there,

21:39.507 --> 21:40.884
their noggins all scrambled.

21:41.008 --> 21:43.386
PHILIP: Oh. Well,
let's search everybody, then.

21:43.511 --> 21:46.606
God-bothering Miss Brent.
Let's search Wargrave.

21:46.722 --> 21:47.723
- What, the judge?
- Mm-hmm.

21:47.848 --> 21:49.145
Well known as a hanging judge.

21:49.266 --> 21:51.394
He's infamous
for the black square.

21:51.519 --> 21:55.114
The story goes that he'd watch
every execution he'd ordered.

21:55.231 --> 21:58.735
Tubs, you've been looking
sideways at Armstrong

21:58.859 --> 22:01.328
all morning,
and now everyone's fair game.

22:01.946 --> 22:03.744
You suggested the judge.

22:03.864 --> 22:05.332
I was taking the piss.

22:05.449 --> 22:10.125
Mr. Owen is on the island,
and I'm going to find him.

22:11.539 --> 22:14.292
You don't want to pay attention
to what he said.

22:14.416 --> 22:17.135
He's just stirring the shit pot.

22:17.795 --> 22:21.049
Well, I can stir it right back.

22:26.136 --> 22:29.140
[ Birds crying in distance]

22:33.853 --> 22:35.947
[Thunder rumbling ]

23:23.444 --> 23:25.446
[ Gasps ]

23:50.471 --> 23:52.644
DR. ARMSTRONG:
[ Grunts ]

23:56.060 --> 23:57.733
PHILIP:
Don't look.

23:59.980 --> 24:02.108
Someone did this?

24:02.232 --> 24:04.280
BLORE: Well, it weren't
no bleedin' accident.

24:05.986 --> 24:07.454
It's murder.

24:11.867 --> 24:14.916
He said no one was coming
for us.

24:15.037 --> 24:17.335
<i>He said this was the</i> end.

24:38.811 --> 24:40.529
Miss Claythorne?

24:41.522 --> 24:44.241
“Eight little soldier boys
traveling in Devon.

24:44.358 --> 24:47.453
One said he'd stay there,
and then there were seven.

24:50.531 --> 24:52.408
Count them, Judge.

24:53.158 --> 24:54.626
Count them.

25:00.791 --> 25:03.294
[Thunder crashing ]

25:05.129 --> 25:08.474
[Wind whistling]

25:13.804 --> 25:15.647
VERA:
Cyril!

25:19.268 --> 25:20.986
Run!

25:21.103 --> 25:22.320
Find help!

25:22.438 --> 25:23.985
A boat!

25:24.106 --> 25:25.949
Run!

25:31.155 --> 25:33.578
-Cyril!
-[ Birds crying ]

25:33.699 --> 25:35.701
[ Echoing ]
Cyril!

25:44.251 --> 25:46.049
[Thunder rumbling ]

25:47.921 --> 25:49.548
Miss Claythorne!

25:50.132 --> 25:51.725
I just want to go!

25:51.842 --> 25:53.344
You'd drown!

25:55.095 --> 25:57.018
Please!

26:01.310 --> 26:02.903
Please.

26:03.645 --> 26:04.942
Come inside.

26:05.064 --> 26:06.065
Come. Come.

26:08.901 --> 26:10.278
I've got you.

26:10.402 --> 26:11.824
Don't worry.
It's all right.

26:23.248 --> 26:25.626
PHILIP: I told you Owen
was on the island.

26:25.751 --> 26:27.753
What made you so sure?

26:28.462 --> 26:29.338
Instinct.

26:29.463 --> 26:31.465
We've got to be rational.

26:31.590 --> 26:33.467
Stick with procedure.

26:33.592 --> 26:35.219
Who is this Owen?

26:35.344 --> 26:36.721
And Mrs. Owen.

26:36.845 --> 26:38.813
I don't think there even <i>is</i>
a Mrs. Owen.

26:38.931 --> 26:41.434
BLORE: We must all have
something in common,

26:41.558 --> 26:42.855
someone who knows us all.

26:42.976 --> 26:44.819
Well, how can that be possible?

26:44.937 --> 26:48.737
I can imagine crossing paths
with a doctor, a judge,

26:48.857 --> 26:50.905
but someone like Mr. Lombard?

26:51.026 --> 26:54.826
Well, we've crossed paths now,
haven't we?

26:55.697 --> 27:00.077
Mr. Lombard, Blore tells me
that you have a revolver.

27:01.036 --> 27:02.583
Oh, Tubs.

27:02.704 --> 27:04.377
-Why have you got a gun?
-He's got a gun?

27:04.498 --> 27:06.421
I carry it everywhere.

27:06.542 --> 27:10.012
And it was implied
that I might need it.

27:10.129 --> 27:12.848
Implied?
By whom?

27:14.049 --> 27:16.268
MORRIS:
My client needs a good man

27:16.385 --> 27:19.355
who can handle situations.

27:21.014 --> 27:22.140
Who's your client?

27:22.266 --> 27:23.392
Mr. Owen.

27:23.517 --> 27:25.485
Ulick Norman Owen.

27:25.602 --> 27:27.149
Never heard of him.

27:27.271 --> 27:28.864
But he has heard of you.

27:28.981 --> 27:31.734
Audrey, the box.

27:53.922 --> 27:55.674
It's dangerous, then.

27:55.799 --> 27:58.928
My client believes
that it could become volatile.

27:59.970 --> 28:01.597
I see.

28:02.973 --> 28:06.318
And how would Mr. Owen wish me
to proceed?

28:06.727 --> 28:09.276
He leaves that
to your discretion.

28:09.396 --> 28:11.444
But forewarned is...

28:11.565 --> 28:13.943
ls forearmed.

28:18.071 --> 28:19.914
I understand.

28:27.873 --> 28:31.298
That's who got in touch with me
about the job with Mrs. Owen --

28:31.418 --> 28:33.512
Isaac Morris in Soho.

28:34.338 --> 28:37.217
Soho.
Hmm.

28:38.050 --> 28:42.351
I was invited here by the Owens,
whom I've never heard of,

28:42.471 --> 28:46.021
to join a mutual friend --
Mrs. Culmington.

28:46.141 --> 28:48.394
Perfect place to recover,
it said.

28:48.518 --> 28:52.273
The envelope was postmarked
London, Soho.

28:54.358 --> 28:56.861
A sink of depravity.

28:57.236 --> 28:59.830
A godless desert of vice.

29:00.405 --> 29:02.783
What brings you here,
Miss Brent?

29:02.908 --> 29:04.751
Mrs. Owen wrote to me.

29:04.868 --> 29:06.495
She was interested in my work.

29:07.746 --> 29:10.795
The moral education of girls
of the lower orders.

29:10.916 --> 29:12.759
They have to be taught modesty
and decency

29:12.876 --> 29:17.552
or society will be drowned in a
rising tide of unwanted babies,

29:17.673 --> 29:19.846
all squalling to be fed.

29:20.759 --> 29:23.387
She wanted to contribute
to my cause.

29:24.304 --> 29:25.396
Blore?

29:26.431 --> 29:30.186
I got a letter
from Ulick Norman Owen.

29:31.436 --> 29:34.406
He was impressed
by my standing in the force.

29:34.523 --> 29:38.528
He said if I could see my way
clear to spending some time,

29:38.652 --> 29:41.656
keeping an eye out, that he
would recompense me generously.

29:41.780 --> 29:43.327
Keeping an eye out for what?

29:43.907 --> 29:46.877
BLORE: He said that someone
was here under false pretenses.

29:46.994 --> 29:50.043
He also supplied
a list of guests.

29:50.163 --> 29:51.164
All of you.

29:51.999 --> 29:53.626
Everyone here.

29:53.750 --> 29:57.254
What he <i>didn't</i> say was that
Lombard would have a gun.

29:58.213 --> 30:00.636
DR. ARMSTRONG: ls it
Mr. Owen's voice on the record?

30:00.757 --> 30:02.100
Does anybody recognize it?

30:02.217 --> 30:03.560
Are we forgetting
about the gun here?

30:03.677 --> 30:06.100
There's a Fenian sat over there
with a bloody gun!

30:06.221 --> 30:07.097
Don't blaspheme.

30:07.222 --> 30:08.940
BLORE:
Hand it over. Come on.

30:09.057 --> 30:10.434
Surrender your weapon,
Mr. Lombard.

30:10.559 --> 30:12.732
- Not a chance.
- I could make you.

30:12.853 --> 30:14.070
You can try.

30:14.646 --> 30:17.741
Is Isaac Morris Mr. Owen?

30:17.858 --> 30:19.155
PHILIP:
No.

30:19.735 --> 30:22.409
I'd have found that sweaty
bucket of lard by now.

30:22.529 --> 30:23.781
EMILY:
Jews.

30:23.905 --> 30:25.532
Wherever there's a problem,

30:25.657 --> 30:27.455
there's Jews
at the bottom of it.

30:29.036 --> 30:30.413
Something struck me.

30:30.537 --> 30:31.834
[Thunder rumbling ]

30:31.955 --> 30:34.208
I can't think
why I didn't see it before.

30:36.001 --> 30:38.299
Ulick Norman Owen.

30:38.420 --> 30:41.299
Una Nancy Owen.

30:41.423 --> 30:43.300
- Or...
-[ Paper tears ]

30:48.347 --> 30:50.816
U.N. Owen...

30:52.100 --> 30:53.852
...is "unknown."

30:58.148 --> 31:00.401
It's a riddle, perhaps.

31:00.525 --> 31:02.152
What does it mean?

31:02.277 --> 31:05.247
It means that Mr. Lombard
is right to insist

31:05.364 --> 31:07.913
that the killer
is on the island.

31:08.033 --> 31:10.502
And he's getting very wet
out there.

31:10.619 --> 31:12.667
The killer's not out there.

31:12.788 --> 31:14.756
The killer is in here.

31:15.332 --> 31:17.630
It is one of us.

31:24.299 --> 31:27.303
We've never met each other
before now. Why?

31:27.427 --> 31:30.397
How could I possibly be capable?

31:30.514 --> 31:33.313
Oh, anyone is capable,
Miss Brent.

31:33.433 --> 31:36.186
Forty years on the criminal
bench has taught me that.

31:36.311 --> 31:38.860
- Rogers.
-[ Sighs] Here we go again.

31:38.980 --> 31:40.607
Lining up the next suspect.

31:40.732 --> 31:42.905
You mark my words.
Rogers.

31:43.026 --> 31:44.448
He's an oily bugger.

31:44.569 --> 31:45.695
Slinking around.

31:45.821 --> 31:48.119
EMILY: Going back and forth
during dinner.

31:48.240 --> 31:49.207
He would have had time

31:49.324 --> 31:50.871
to put something
in Mr. Marston's drink.

31:50.992 --> 31:53.165
I heard him tell Mrs. Rogers
to shut up.

31:53.286 --> 31:55.584
Well, she's shut up now,
isn't she?

31:55.705 --> 31:57.252
He's the one moving the figures.

31:57.374 --> 31:59.376
But the -- the general,
the rest of us,

31:59.501 --> 32:02.345
that record, this house --
Why?

32:03.130 --> 32:05.258
BLORE: Rogers -- He's got
low cunning running though him

32:05.382 --> 32:07.476
like Brighton
through a stick of rock.

32:07.592 --> 32:08.559
We need to watch him.

32:08.677 --> 32:12.307
Any faith I ever had
in the thin blue line

32:12.431 --> 32:15.310
evaporated the second I met you,
Tubs.

32:15.434 --> 32:17.732
You call me that one more time,
mate -- one more time --

32:17.853 --> 32:19.105
And you'll what?

32:22.899 --> 32:27.325
We are all being hunted.

32:27.904 --> 32:30.657
There's someone else
on this island,

32:30.782 --> 32:31.829
and when I find him,

32:31.950 --> 32:35.545
I'm gonna make him number <i>22</i>
with a bullet right there.

32:35.662 --> 32:36.629
<i>Oh, God.</i>

32:36.746 --> 32:40.046
How could you say that...
so easily?

32:40.167 --> 32:43.046
I just open my mouth,
and it comes out.

32:44.004 --> 32:46.723
[ Door opens]

32:47.883 --> 32:50.511
I'll see what can be done
about supper.

32:50.635 --> 32:53.263
There's some liver and kidneys.

32:53.388 --> 32:56.358
Perhaps a pie
with some good gravy.

32:57.809 --> 33:00.312
That would be delicious, Rogers.

33:00.812 --> 33:01.813
Thank you.

33:01.938 --> 33:04.032
Thank you, Rogers.

33:06.485 --> 33:07.702
[ Door closes]

33:07.819 --> 33:11.198
Well, I ain't eating a mouthful
of his pie.

33:39.643 --> 33:42.647
[Thunder rumbling,
wind whistling]

33:54.824 --> 33:56.121
Oh.
Well, good night.

33:56.243 --> 33:58.337
[Thunder crashes]

34:00.288 --> 34:02.290
Trust in God.

34:03.250 --> 34:07.596
But perhaps also...
we should lock our doors.

34:15.512 --> 34:17.606
[Thunder crashes]

34:17.722 --> 34:22.728
[ Indistinct voices]

34:34.781 --> 34:36.954
EMILY: The Lord is my shepherd.
I shall not want.

34:37.074 --> 34:38.418
[Thunder rumbling ]

34:38.534 --> 34:40.833
He maketh me to lie down
in green pastures.

34:40.954 --> 34:42.627
He leadeth me
beside the still waters.

34:42.746 --> 34:44.498
He restoreth my soul.

34:44.623 --> 34:46.877
[Rain falling]

35:07.606 --> 35:10.735
[Thunder crashing,
wind whistling]

35:13.528 --> 35:15.530
[Window closes]

35:32.672 --> 35:34.800
He leadeth me
in the paths of righteousness

35:34.924 --> 35:36.892
for his name's sake.

35:37.010 --> 35:38.307
Yea, though I walk through --

35:38.428 --> 35:41.728
WOMAN: ...the valley
of the shadow of death,

35:41.848 --> 35:46.194
I will fear no evil,
for Thou art with me.

35:46.311 --> 35:48.313
[Thunder rumbling ]

35:58.365 --> 36:00.459
I will fear no evil.

36:00.575 --> 36:02.543
I will fear no evil.
I will --

36:02.661 --> 36:03.628
[ Gasps ]

36:03.745 --> 36:05.713
I will fear no evil.
Thou art with me.

36:05.830 --> 36:07.924
[Whimpers]

36:08.875 --> 36:10.877
[Thunder crashes]

36:24.265 --> 36:26.267
[ Footsteps approaching ]

36:29.979 --> 36:33.734
Get up!

36:34.776 --> 36:37.495
Get up!
[ Gong chiming ]

36:38.988 --> 36:40.615
Get up!

36:44.744 --> 36:46.291
I was looking for him.

36:46.413 --> 36:47.380
[Gags]

36:47.497 --> 36:48.623
I wanted a coffee.

36:48.748 --> 36:50.125
I looked.

36:50.250 --> 36:52.002
And I found this.

36:54.671 --> 36:56.548
It wasn't me.

36:56.673 --> 36:58.050
I just wanted a damn coffee.

36:58.174 --> 36:59.175
It wasn't me.

36:59.300 --> 37:01.268
He's been here all night.

37:01.386 --> 37:04.310
Seven little soldiers
chopping up sticks.

37:04.431 --> 37:07.560
One chopped himself in half,
and then there were six.

37:08.810 --> 37:10.027
So she's right.

37:11.563 --> 37:12.735
It is the poem.

37:14.023 --> 37:15.821
But he's fucked,
Mr. Unknown Owen,

37:15.942 --> 37:20.072
because six little solder boys
played with a hive.

37:20.196 --> 37:22.244
A bumblebee stung one,
and then there were five.

37:22.365 --> 37:24.333
And there is no hive here,
and there are no bees,

37:24.451 --> 37:26.419
so what are you gonna do now,
Mr. Unknown Owen?

37:26.536 --> 37:28.379
You're fucked!
You're fuck--

37:33.418 --> 37:34.670
Now get dressed.

37:35.253 --> 37:40.680
We will all get dressed,
and I will make coffee.

37:41.259 --> 37:43.307
Miss Brent, shall we?

37:43.428 --> 37:44.475
Yes.

37:48.975 --> 37:50.101
Shit.

37:50.226 --> 37:51.569
Shit the bed.

37:51.686 --> 37:53.734
PHILIP: We'll need to find
something to wrap him up with

37:53.855 --> 37:55.232
or he's gonna go everywhere.

37:56.649 --> 37:59.118
[Thunder rumbling ]

37:59.235 --> 38:01.829
[Clock ticking, rain falling]

38:07.202 --> 38:09.375
[ Footsteps approaching ]

38:17.378 --> 38:18.721
Coffee.

38:20.048 --> 38:22.142
There's no milk, I'm afraid.

38:22.258 --> 38:27.059
Does this person...
mean to kill us all?

38:28.515 --> 38:30.142
I believe so, yes.

38:34.687 --> 38:36.860
I've lost a ball of wool.
[ Sighs]

38:38.066 --> 38:41.286
I'm quite ridiculously
distressed about it.

38:43.029 --> 38:45.031
It's only wool.

38:53.414 --> 38:55.416
I'm so very tired.

38:59.254 --> 39:01.177
Drink your coffee, Miss Brent.

39:01.756 --> 39:04.134
I'll bring you a candle
to see by.

39:04.259 --> 39:05.806
Thank you, dear.

39:43.006 --> 39:45.509
[Thunder rumbling,
rain falling]

39:53.808 --> 39:55.355
I'll make some more.

40:20.376 --> 40:24.927
Judge Wargrave, I feel I owe you
an apology for...

40:25.048 --> 40:28.018
exposing your illness in such
an unforgivable fashion.

40:28.134 --> 40:31.559
We're all feeling
a little ragged, understandably.

40:39.437 --> 40:41.314
What's your opinion
of the others?

40:42.273 --> 40:43.775
I haven't really formed one.

40:43.900 --> 40:45.823
I don't trust any of them.

40:45.944 --> 40:46.991
Blore.

40:47.111 --> 40:48.237
That bastard Lombard.

40:48.363 --> 40:49.455
Claythorne.

40:49.572 --> 40:51.791
Miss Brent
and her religious mania.

40:54.035 --> 40:59.166
But you and I...
we have sharp minds.

41:00.208 --> 41:03.337
Actual intellects.

41:05.171 --> 41:06.969
We should stay together.

41:07.966 --> 41:09.218
Hm.

41:10.343 --> 41:11.765
Very well.

41:19.602 --> 41:21.070
Oh.

41:21.771 --> 41:23.819
Here.
Here.

41:23.940 --> 41:25.783
Thank you.

41:25.900 --> 41:29.029
[Voice breaking ] Dribbling
down myself like a child.

41:35.368 --> 41:37.996
Miss Claythorne's making
the coffee.

41:39.831 --> 41:41.754
She should be watched.

41:49.632 --> 41:52.135
[ Breathing heavily]

41:54.971 --> 41:57.144
[Grunts]

42:01.811 --> 42:04.064
Right.
[ Exhales deeply]

42:04.188 --> 42:06.282
<i>You do the stairs.</i>

42:06.399 --> 42:09.494
I'm going to wash the guts
out of the wood store.

42:16.659 --> 42:18.753
[Water dripping ]

42:33.509 --> 42:36.353
[ Door opens,
footsteps approaching ]

42:42.810 --> 42:44.312
Can I?

42:47.440 --> 42:49.534
[ Dishware rattling ]

42:50.234 --> 42:53.363
I rather enjoy domestic tasks.

42:54.113 --> 42:55.956
They are soothing.

42:57.033 --> 42:58.376
Normal.

42:59.494 --> 43:00.495
Indeed.

43:18.429 --> 43:20.557
I'll just be a moment.

43:20.681 --> 43:22.854
All right.

43:32.360 --> 43:34.237
[ Hinges squeak]

43:34.362 --> 43:36.456
[Thunder rumbling ]

44:45.766 --> 44:47.439
[Gong chiming]

45:20.968 --> 45:23.437
VERA:
Stung by a bee.

45:25.848 --> 45:27.225
And then there were five.

45:27.350 --> 45:29.352
[Thunder crashes]

45:49.372 --> 45:53.002
Well, I suppose with no Rogers,
I should think about lunch.

45:53.125 --> 45:55.628
I could eat a scabby horse.

45:56.254 --> 45:57.801
You're actually hungry?

45:58.714 --> 46:02.685
Well, it was heavy work...
dealing with Rogers.

46:02.802 --> 46:04.429
And you're the one
who suggested lunch.

46:04.553 --> 46:07.727
Only because it's what one does
at this time of day.

46:07.848 --> 46:08.724
But I'm not hungry.

46:08.849 --> 46:10.021
How could you possibly
be hungry?

46:10.142 --> 46:12.110
Oi, you.

46:12.228 --> 46:16.199
Don't go implying...
casting aspersions --

46:16.315 --> 46:18.784
I've got -- I've got nothing
to do with this.

46:18.901 --> 46:20.198
I've got nothing to do
with any of it.

46:20.319 --> 46:21.787
Just because I said
that I was hungry --

46:21.904 --> 46:24.407
I am hungry.
It doesn't prove a single thing.

46:26.909 --> 46:28.911
I'm going to get dressed.

46:35.293 --> 46:39.264
The whole morning, dragging
Rogers around, clearing up guts,

46:39.380 --> 46:41.257
without so much as a cup of tea
to wet me whistle.

46:41.382 --> 46:42.554
And you --
You look at me like --

46:42.675 --> 46:45.303
Calm down.

46:47.054 --> 46:48.431
You've got some front, love.

46:49.849 --> 46:52.568
You've got
some right brass neck.

46:55.813 --> 46:58.737
PHILIP:
Don't go downstairs on your own.

46:58.858 --> 47:00.485
Not with those two.

47:01.569 --> 47:02.946
What, Wargrave and Armstrong?

47:03.070 --> 47:04.868
Mm-hmm.

47:04.989 --> 47:07.117
You wait up here for me.

47:29.972 --> 47:34.227
It was locked, which means
there must be a master key.

47:34.352 --> 47:35.854
Rogers must have had
a master key.

47:35.978 --> 47:37.355
You two dealt with the body!

47:37.480 --> 47:39.357
And you found it.

47:39.482 --> 47:40.904
Or did you?

47:41.025 --> 47:42.743
You shrieking like a woman.

47:42.860 --> 47:44.612
Was that a bit
of amateur dramatics, was it?

47:44.737 --> 47:47.616
I did nothing to Rogers.
I didn't take any master key.

47:47.740 --> 47:49.913
We don't even know if there <i>is</i>
a master key.

47:50.034 --> 47:51.957
And we only have your word
that the gun was stolen!

47:52.078 --> 47:54.547
- You could've taken it!
- Why would I steal my own gun?

47:54.663 --> 47:57.166
I don't know
why you'd do anything, Lombard.

47:57.291 --> 47:59.214
I don't know
why you killed Rogers

47:59.335 --> 48:01.008
or Miss Brent or MacArthur!

48:01.128 --> 48:02.004
I didn't kill them.

48:02.129 --> 48:03.676
Well, you <i>would</i> say that,
wouldn't you?

48:03.798 --> 48:06.597
Just like you'd say
that your gun was stolen!

48:06.717 --> 48:11.348
You really are a first-class,
five-star,

48:11.472 --> 48:14.271
solid-gold fucking moron.

48:14.392 --> 48:16.065
WARGRAVE:
Please. The lady. Mm?

48:16.185 --> 48:18.529
BLORE:
Double bluff.

48:21.107 --> 48:22.359
What, Tubs?

48:22.483 --> 48:24.110
BLORE: Why you would steal
your own gun.

48:24.235 --> 48:25.828
Armstrong's got a point.

48:25.945 --> 48:27.788
It's all riddles and games,
smoke and mirrors.

48:27.905 --> 48:29.498
Double bluff.

48:30.908 --> 48:32.876
You were the last one down.

48:34.745 --> 48:36.668
The last one.

48:37.456 --> 48:39.504
Ages behind everyone else.

48:39.625 --> 48:41.627
What -- What took you so long?

48:44.004 --> 48:45.256
I don't care to say.

48:45.381 --> 48:47.600
PHILIP:
You killed Rogers.

48:48.175 --> 48:50.473
You took the master key.
You went to bed.

48:50.594 --> 48:52.221
You made sure all of us
were downstairs.

48:52.346 --> 48:54.269
And then you got into my room
and you took my gun.

48:54.390 --> 48:55.607
You have my gun,
you little prick.

48:55.724 --> 48:56.896
Lombard.
For heaven's sake.

48:57.017 --> 48:58.234
I never killed Rogers,

48:58.352 --> 49:00.525
and I ain't got your key
or your sodding gun.

49:00.646 --> 49:01.863
PHILIP:
Then what took you so long?

49:01.981 --> 49:04.200
If you weren't in my room
stealing my gun,

49:04.316 --> 49:05.613
then why were you the last down?

49:05.734 --> 49:08.783
I was in the bloody lavvy,
if you must know.

49:08.904 --> 49:10.531
Constipated!

49:10.656 --> 49:13.330
DR. ARMSTRONG:
[ Laughs]

49:14.326 --> 49:15.623
<i>Oh, yes.</i>

49:15.744 --> 49:18.042
Yeah.
Laugh it up.

49:18.164 --> 49:20.337
-It's not funny.
-[ Laughter continues]

49:20.458 --> 49:22.881
I was bound up something rotten.

49:23.461 --> 49:26.214
Sat there in a muck sweat.

49:26.338 --> 49:28.136
So it weren't me.

49:28.257 --> 49:29.884
It could have been any of us.

49:31.218 --> 49:34.438
Any one of us
could have had the key.

49:34.555 --> 49:37.354
Any one of us
could have the gun.

49:37.475 --> 49:40.274
[Clock ticking ]

49:48.569 --> 49:50.571
[ Drawer closes]

49:56.785 --> 49:58.958
It is the only way to be sure.

50:01.582 --> 50:03.676
BLORE: It's not like you've been
singled out.

50:03.792 --> 50:06.011
We're all getting the same.

50:21.435 --> 50:23.529
[ Drawer closes]

50:24.939 --> 50:26.065
BLORE:
No key.

50:26.190 --> 50:27.487
No gun.

50:29.818 --> 50:33.539
Now...Now you, Miss Claythorne.

50:33.656 --> 50:35.203
Of course.

50:54.885 --> 50:57.104
I'm just being thorough.

51:22.788 --> 51:25.291
CYRIL:
You like Uncle Hugo, don't you?

51:25.416 --> 51:27.043
VERA:
I do.

51:27.167 --> 51:29.465
I'm in love with him.

51:29.587 --> 51:31.339
I love him so much it hurts.

51:31.463 --> 51:32.430
Silly.

51:32.548 --> 51:34.300
Girls are silly.

51:34.425 --> 51:35.802
[ Chuckles ]

51:35.926 --> 51:37.974
And I'm going to marry him.

51:38.095 --> 51:40.974
I heard Mummy say he couldn't
afford to get married.

51:41.557 --> 51:43.434
Well, I'll find a way, Cyril.

51:43.559 --> 51:44.856
If you marry Uncle Hugo...

51:44.977 --> 51:46.695
<i>When</i> I marry Hugo.

51:46.812 --> 51:48.064
...will you be my aunt?

51:48.188 --> 51:49.064
I will.

51:49.189 --> 51:51.066
Aunt Vera.

51:51.191 --> 51:52.784
And what fun we'll have.

51:52.901 --> 51:56.326
Christmas and birthdays
and summer holidays.

51:56.447 --> 51:59.826
Picnics, parties, pony rides.

51:59.950 --> 52:00.746
Hm.

52:00.868 --> 52:03.587
How happy we'll be
when we have everything.

52:04.455 --> 52:07.459
[Thunder rumbling,
rain falling]

52:40.908 --> 52:43.331
Cyril!

52:46.872 --> 52:50.046
[ Screams ]

53:00.469 --> 53:02.563
[ Gasps ]

53:07.893 --> 53:09.691
DR. ARMSTRONG:
[ Sighs ]

53:09.812 --> 53:12.440
Why isn't Lombard doing this?

53:13.148 --> 53:18.325
Blore and I thought it a
good idea to keep you two apart.

54:22.801 --> 54:25.395
Well, well, Miss Claythorne.

54:27.765 --> 54:29.859
Mr. Lombard.

54:29.975 --> 54:31.648
Philip.

54:33.020 --> 54:34.613
Vera.

54:41.153 --> 54:43.451
[ Door opens]

54:47.659 --> 54:49.457
Nothing.

54:49.578 --> 54:51.546
We'll search the rest
of the house.

54:51.663 --> 54:53.210
Every room.

55:11.350 --> 55:13.273
[Wood clattering ]

55:21.068 --> 55:22.661
[ Metal scraping ]

55:58.021 --> 55:59.739
[ Clattering ]

55:59.857 --> 56:02.360
[Thunder rumbling ]

56:04.027 --> 56:06.530
[Clock ticking ]

56:26.508 --> 56:29.011
[Thunder rumbling,
rain falling]

56:40.480 --> 56:42.482
[Clock chiming]

57:08.091 --> 57:09.718
BLORE:
We're in hell.

57:10.427 --> 57:13.226
And we're being punished
for what we done.

57:13.347 --> 57:14.690
WARGRAVE:
He refused the hood.

57:14.806 --> 57:16.023
He haunts me still.

57:16.141 --> 57:17.768
DR. ARMSTRONG: [Whispering ]
Look at them.

57:17.893 --> 57:20.066
There's something going on
between them.

57:20.979 --> 57:22.777
VERA:
Someone has to come for us soon.

57:22.898 --> 57:24.320
They -- They have to.

57:24.441 --> 57:26.819
BLORE:
I reckon we're being watched.

57:28.820 --> 57:30.197
[ Growls ]

57:30.322 --> 57:31.619
We are.

